What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The Video Game Sales dataset collected from Kaggle website. The dataset consistes of information about more than 10000 Video Games, it contains 11 columns and 16291 rows. Including, name, year, genre, publisher, and global sales. The dataset contains both qualitative and quantitative types of data.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

It is interesting that the dataset combines all the famous publisher companies around the world. Also, it provides the total sales for the top countries how interested in video games.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I believe that the year will have the strongest effect on the other variables such as the number of video games published and the increase in the total sales in each country.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I will start to do visualization for the individual variables and look at each different variable at a time.

What is the number of video games released among all the years?¶

In [16]:
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
In [27]:
# display the number of video games released by year
plt.figure(figsize=[10, 7])
sb.countplot(data=df, x='Year', color=base_color);
plt.title("Number of Video Games Released", fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Count", fontsize=14)
# Use xticks to rotate the category labels
plt.xticks(rotation=90);

The above figure shows the number of video games released from 1980 to 2020. It is clear that the number of video games started to increase year by year. However, in 2009 the number of videos games released started to decrease.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Nothing seems out of normal for the Video Game Sales dataset. Moreover, I didn't need to clean the data, except changing the data types.

Bivariate Exploration¶

In this section, I will look at the pairwise correlations present between features in the data.

What is the relationship between all variables?¶

In [45]:
numeric_vars = ['Year', 'NA_Sales', 'EU_Sales', 'JP_Sales', 'Other_Sales', 'Global_Sales']
categoric_vars = ['Platform', 'Genre', 'Publisher']
In [51]:
# correlation plot
plt.figure(figsize = [10, 7])
sb.heatmap(df[numeric_vars].corr(), annot = True, fmt = '.3f',
           cmap = 'vlag_r', center = 0)
plt.show()

The above figure shows the correlation between all the numeric variables. Also, the values were highlited with different colors based on the correlation values between each variable. For inctance, it is clear that we have a strong correlation between global sales and NA sales. Also, there are a weak correlation between JP sales and the year variable.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

I noticed that the global sales had a strong impact on the JP sales, EU sales, NA sales, and other sales. It shows a direct relationship between these variables since the increase in global sales results in increasing in the other variables.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

It is intersting how the action video games releases were higher than the other types, and platform got a very low number of video games released. However, the platform got a higher number of global sales.

What is the relationship between sales in Europe, Japan, and North America?¶

In [148]:
plt.scatter(data = df, x = 'EU_Sales', y = 'JP_Sales', s = 'NA_Sales')

# dummy series for adding legend
sizes = [20, 40, 50]
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
legend_obj = []
for s in sizes:
    legend_obj.append(plt.scatter([], [], s = s, color = base_color))
plt.legend(legend_obj, ['Europe','Japan','North America'])
plt.title("Sales Among Europe, Japan, and North America", fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel('Sales (millions)', fontsize=14);
plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=14);

The above scatter plot shows the relationship between sales in Europe, Japan, and North America. It is clear from the figure that the sales were around 0 and 5 million.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I observed that the year variable has an impact on all the other variables including, global sales, other sales, EU sales, NA sales, JP sales. The result of this may be the improvement of the technology year after year. And what confirms this is that Europe, Japan, and North America sales were all increasing together along with incease the year.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

It is interesting how the global sales values for each genre was almost close during all years.

Summary¶

  • The number of video games started to increase year by year. However, in 2009 the number of videos games released started to decrease.
  • DS and PS2 platforms have the highest number of video games released among all other platforms.
  • The action video games has the highest number of released.
  • There are only few puzzle video games.
  • Most of the video games released after 2000.
